{"title_page": "Mercedes-Benz Vito", "text_new": "{{short description|A light commercial van}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Mercedes-Benz V Class/Vito\n| image = Mercedes-Benz V 250 d Exclusive AMG Line Lang (V 447) \u2013 Frontansicht, 29. Juni 2016, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg\n| aka = {{unbulleted list|Mercedes-Benz Vito (Van)|Mercedes-Benz Viano (MPV)|Mercedes-Benz V-Class (MPV)|Mercedes-Benz Marco Polo (Campervan)|Mercedes-Benz Metris (North American Models)|Mercedes-Benz EQV (electric)|Mercedes-Benz eVito Tourer (electric)}}\n| manufacturer = [[Daimler-Benz]] (1996\u20131998)<br>[[DaimlerChrysler]] (1998\u20132007)<br>[[Daimler AG]] (2007\u2013present)\n| production = 1996\u2013present\n| assembly = Spain: [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]] (Mercedes-Benz Espana, S.A.)\n| predecessor = [[Mercedes-Benz MB100]]<br>[[Mercedes-Benz R-Class]]\n| class = [[Light commercial vehicle]] ([[M-segment|M]])\n| body_style = [[Van]]<br/>[[Minibus]]\n| layout = \n| engine = 2.0 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM654 engine|OM654]] [[Inline-four engine|I4]] CDI Diesel<br /> 2.1 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM651 engine|OM651]] [[Inline-four engine|I4]] CDI Diesel<br />3.0 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM642 engine|OM642]] [[V6 engine|V6]] CDI Diesel\n| transmission = 5-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]<br />6-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]<br /> 7-speed automatic\n| related = \n}}\n\nThe '''Mercedes-Benz Vito''' is a [[light commercial vehicle|light commercial]] [[van]] ([[M-segment|M]]) produced by [[Mercedes-Benz]]. It is available as a standard [[panel van]] for cargo (called Vito), or with passenger accommodations substituted for part or all of the load area (called '''V-Class''' or '''Viano''').\n\nThe V-Class/Viano is a [[Minivan|large MPV]]. The first generation went on sale in 1996. The second generation was introduced in 2004, and the vehicle received the new Viano name. In 2010, the vehicle was facelifted with revised front and rear bumpers and lights. The interior was also improved with upgraded materials and new technology. The third generation was launched in 2014 and returned to being called V-Class.\n\nThe Viano is available in both rear- and four-wheel-drive configurations and comes in three lengths, two wheelbases and a choice of four petrol and diesel engines (as well as two specialist tuned models) coupled to either a six-speed manual or five-speed [[Tiptronic|TouchShift]] automatic transmission.\n__TOC__\n{{clear}}\n\n=={{Anchor|W638}}First generation (W638; 1996\u20132003)==\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz V 220 CDI Trend (W 638) \u2013 Frontansicht, 12. August 2013, Velbert.jpg|thumb|left|Mercedes-Benz V-Klasse (front)]]\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz V 220 CDI Trend (W 638) \u2013 Heckansicht, 12. August 2013, Velbert.jpg|thumb|Mercedes-Benz V-Klasse (rear)]]\n\nThe first generation [[Mercedes-Benz]] Vito was produced between 1996 and 2003. It is powered either by a diesel engine with up to {{convert|120|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} or a gasoline engine with up to {{convert|140|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} and a [[front-wheel drive]] drivetrain. The range of gasoline engines consists of two old units from Mercedes (113 and 114) and a [[Volkswagen]] 2.8 VR6 engine, designated as the M104.900. When it comes to diesel engines, old 2.3 with and without turbo and also modern CDI 2.2 engines are available.\n\nThis body design was also sold as the V-Klasse in more luxurious and expensive version (V-Klasse was replaced with the Viano-name for the second generation of Vito). The Viano also included less van like features to the Vito such as only two seats in the front and a larger and more spacious seating capacity. At first many Vito drivers who wanted a spacious, small van opted for the Vito microbus which was extremely similar to the Viano, apart from its more van like and less luxurious features. The Viano was however a good, more car like option to the Vito microbus.  It was designed by Michael Mauer from 1989 to 1991, when the final design was chosen and patented in February 1993.<ref>[http://press.porsche.com/more_about/executives/pag/mauer.php \"Mercedes-Benz Vito\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202081500/http://press.porsche.com/more_about/executives/pag/mauer.php |date=2 February 2017 }}. ''Press Porsche''. Retrieved 2 June 2014.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n=={{Anchor|W639}}Second generation (W639; 2003\u20132014)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = W639\n| image = Mercedes vito 2 v sst.jpg\n| aka = Mercedes-Benz Viano<br />Mercedes-Benz Valente (Australia)<br />Mercedes-Benz V-Class (Japan)\n| assembly = {{ubl |Spain: [[Vitoria, Spain|Vitoria-Gasteiz]] (Mercedes-Benz Espana, S.A.) |Spain: [[Alcobendas]] ([[Complete knock down|CKD]]) |Mexico: [[Santiago Tianguistenco]] |China: [[Fuzhou|F\u00fazh\u014du]] ([[Fujian Daimler Automotive|Fujian Daimler]])}}\n| production = 2003\u20132014 (Spain)<br />2008\u2013present (Mexico)<br />2010\u20132015 (China)\n| body_style = 4-door [[van]]<br/>4-door [[minibus]]\n| engine = 2.1 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM646 engine#OM646 DE22 LA|OM646 980]] [[Straight-4|L4]] Turbo Diesel (China)<br>2.1 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM646 engine|OM646 DE22 LA R]] [[Straight-4|L4]] Diesel<br>2.1 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM651 engine|OM651 DE22]] [[Straight-4|L4]] Diesel<br>3.0 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM642 engine|OM642]] [[V6]] Diesel<br>2.5 L [[Mercedes-Benz M272 engine#E25|M272 924]] [[V6]] Diesel (China)<br>3.0 L [[Mercedes-Benz M272 engine#E30|M272 939]] [[V6]] Diesel (China)<br>3.2 L [[Mercedes-Benz M112 engine|M112 E32]] [[V6]] Petrol (2010\u2013)<br>3.5 L [[Mercedes-Benz M272 engine|M272 E35]] [[V6]] Petrol<br>3.7 L [[Mercedes-Benz M112 engine|M112 E37]] [[V6]] Petrol<br>4.3 L Brabus [[V6]] Petrol<br>6.0 L [[Mercedes-Benz M119 engine|M119]] Brabus [[V8 engine|V8]] Twin-Turbo Petrol\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Manual transmission|Manual]]<br>5-speed [[Automatic transmission|TouchShift (Automatic)]]\n| layout = [[Front engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FR Layout]]<br>[[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|F4 Layout]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|3200|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (SWB) <br> {{convert|3430|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (LWB)\n| length = {{convert|4748|-|5223|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1906|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1875|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|2040|-|2135|kg|abbr=on}}\n}}\n[[File:Mercedes W639 rear 20080127.jpg|thumb|The rear of the Second generation Vito|alt=|left]]\nSix or seven seats come as standard in most markets. The Viano can be turned into an eight-seat people carrier by fitting two three-seater benches in the rear. All rear seats slide in 1-inch (2.5&nbsp;cm) increments, recline and can be turned to face one other. They can also be folded down or removed completely to increase the load capacity. A rear folding table is standard in six- and seven-seat layouts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/overview/design.0003.html |title=Mercedes-Benz UK - Overview - Design |publisher=.mercedes-benz.co.uk |accessdate=4 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724202502/http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/overview/design.0003.html |archivedate=24 July 2010}}</ref> The rear seats cannot be folded into the floor like on some rivals.\n\nWith all the seats removed the Viano Extra-Long can accommodate up to {{convert|4610|L|cuft}} of cargo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/overview/design.0004.html |title=Mercedes-Benz UK - Overview - Design |publisher=.mercedes-benz.co.uk |accessdate=4 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623052221/http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/overview/design.0004.html |archivedate=23 June 2010 }}</ref> with a payload of {{convert|930|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/technicaldata.html |title=Mercedes-Benz UK - Viano - Technical data |publisher=.mercedes-benz.co.uk |accessdate=4 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619112003/http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/technicaldata.html |archivedate=19 June 2010}}</ref> It can tow a {{convert|2500|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} braked trailer and a {{convert|750|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} unbraked trailer. An adjustable self-levelling rear suspension is included on higher specification models.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/equipment_accessories/standard_optional_equipment.0005.html |title=Mercedes-Benz UK - Lines and equipment - Standard equipment |publisher=.mercedes-benz.co.uk |accessdate=4 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514214057/http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/equipment_accessories/standard_optional_equipment.0005.html |archivedate=14 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nRear-wheel drive allows the Viano to have a smaller turning circle than front-wheel drive rivals; Compact and Long models have a turning circle of {{convert|11.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} whereas the Extra-Long model turns in {{convert|12.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatcar.com/Review/EditionCompare?newOrUsed=New&makeId=13298&modelId=14658&editionId=14674&makeId1=13298&modelId1=14658&editionId1=14675&makeId2=13298&modelId2=14658&editionId2=14676 |title=Mercedes-Benz Viano MPV 3.0 CDI Ambiente SWB 5dr - Car Comparison - What Car? |publisher=Whatcar.com |accessdate=26 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727001453/http://www.whatcar.com/Review/EditionCompare?newOrUsed=New&makeId=13298&modelId=14658&editionId=14674&makeId1=13298&modelId1=14658&editionId1=14675&makeId2=13298&modelId2=14658&editionId2=14676 |archivedate=27 July 2011  }}</ref>\n\nJapan passenger models were sold as the V-Class, as the V 350. Early models included V 350 Trend (RHD), V 350 Ambiente (RHD), V 350 Ambiente long (RHD).<ref>[http://www.mercedes-benz.jp/news/release/2011/20110121.pdf \u30e1\u30eb\u30bb\u30c7\u30b9\u30fb\u30d9\u30f3\u30c4\u65b0\u578bV \u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u3092\u767a\u58f2]</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mercedes-Benz released the Valente model in Australia to sit beneath the Viano as the entry-level passenger van.\n\n===Initial release===\n\n====Vito====\n{{Multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 220\n| image1 = Beijing Emergency Medical Centre MB Vito.jpg\n| image2 = A 999 RTW \u4eacMX9638@2.jpg\n| caption2 = Mercedes-Benz Vito Ambulance in Beijing, China\n}}\nThe Vito was launched in China in April 2010. Engine choices consisted of the 2.1 litre [[Mercedes-Benz OM646 engine|OM646]] turbo diesel four-cylinder, the 2.5 litre [[Mercedes-Benz M272 engine|M272]] diesel V6 and the 3 litre diesel V6 which also uses the M272 name. A 6 speed manual gearbox is standard for four cylinder diesel variants while V6 diesel variants are equipped to a 5 speed automatic gearbox. Trims levels are available known as the 2.1T Diesel Elite. 2.1T Diesel Service, 2.5L Elite, 2.5L Service, 3.0L Service and 3.0L Business. Pricing ranges from 316,000 yuan to 389,000 yuan (46,000 to 55,830 USD - March 2020 exchange rate).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://car.autohome.com.cn/config/spec/7347.html#pvareaid=3454541|title=2010 Mercedes Benz Vito 2.1 litre diesel amd 2.5 litre V6 diesel specs (Chinese market)}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://car.autohome.com.cn/config/spec/15505.html#pvareaid=3454541|title=2013 Mercedes Benz Vito 3 litre V6 diesel specs (Chinese market)}}</ref> For actual car badging, the 2.1 litre Diesel models were known as the 115 CDI, the 119 for 2.5 litre V6 models and the 122 for 3 litre V6 models. The W639 Vito was then succeeded by the W447 in 2016 although most Vitos of the W639 variant are still in use for the Chinese market as of 2020 as ambulance vans in Beijing. \n \nThe second generation [[Mercedes-Benz]] Vito design that is more streamlined than its predecessor, powered by a new range of engines, and a [[rear-wheel drive]](RWD) drivetrain.\n\nThe angle of the [[windshield]] and [[pillar (car)|A-pillar]] is closer to [[Horizontal plane|horizontal]]; the [[dashboard]] is bigger and the [[hood (vehicle)|bonnet]] (hood) smaller. The new Vito is available in three different lengths and four diesel engine versions: the 109 CDI, 111 CDI, 115 CDI (all powered by a 4-cylinder 2.2-litre engine) and the 120 CDI (featuring the 3.0-litre V6 unit). The model numerics relate to their engine power output: currently the 109 has {{convert|95|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}}, the 111 has {{convert|116|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}}, the 115 has {{convert|150|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}, and the 120 has {{convert|204|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Blue-efficiency technology is optional. The vehicles have a new 6-speed manual gearbox gear ratios designed for fuel economy. The second generation Vitos are [[European emission standards|Euro]] 3 compliant (additionally Euro 4 compliant as of November 2006) and exempt from the [[London low emission zone|Low Emission Zone]] in London, which requires commercial vehicles (vans) to reach at least Euro 3 standard from October 2010.\n\n====Vito London Taxi====\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz VITO London taxicab.jpg|thumb|Vito London Taxi|alt=|left]]\nIn August 2008, a variant of the Vito was approved by the [[Public Carriage Office]] for use as a licensed London '[[Hackney carriage|black cab]]'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Public Carriage Office notice at Transport for London |url=http://www.glaciervehicles.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/13-08-mercedes-benz-vito-taxi.pdf |accessdate=8 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714113453/http://www.glaciervehicles.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/13-08-mercedes-benz-vito-taxi.pdf |archivedate=14 July 2014  }}</ref> The Vito taxicab includes electric sliding doors, electric steps and seating for six people. The Vito's rear-wheel steering enables it to meet the PCO's strict [[Conditions of Fitness]] requirements including a {{convert|25|ft|m|abbr=on}} turning circle and wheelchair accessibility.<ref>[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23500360-details/Hail,+the+new+London+cab/article.do Hail, the new London cab], ''London Evening Standard'', 26 June 2008  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819223034/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23500360-details/Hail%2C%2Bthe%2Bnew%2BLondon%2Bcab/article.do |date=19 August 2008 }}</ref> The vehicle, a variation of the 'Traveliner' model, is built by Penso in Coventry. The rear wheel steer system is licensed from one80, and it is distributed through Eco City Vehicles subsidiary KPM-UK Taxis.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/transport/2791681/Mercedes-Benz-to-launch-eco-friendly-London-black-cab.html Mercedes-Benz to launch eco-friendly London black cab], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 17 June 2008</ref>\n\nThe new Taxi does not perform the famous U-turn in the same way as the TX and Metro models {{clarify |date=July 2017 |reason= which cars are referred to here?}}, instead it incorporates an electrically operated rear wheel system, activated by a button adjacent to the steering wheel. This turns the rear wheels in the opposite direction to the front wheels, thus allowing the Taxi to perform the same tight turning circle as the TX and Metro models. This system is only possible when the vehicle is traveling at less than {{convert|5|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}, and if the vehicle goes over this speed while the LSM is active, it is deactivated, and the wheels straighten up.\n\nIt is longer and wider than the TX models, but traveling through tight spaces is aided by the electric folding wing mirrors, which as of 2009 are standard.\n\n====Viano Marco Polo====\n[[File:Vianomarcopolo1.png|thumb|Viano Marco Polo camping edition]]\n\nIn some countries a camping derivative is available - known as the Marco Polo - equipped with a galley (including gas stove, sink, 40 L fridge, and storage), multi-function wardrobe and a sliding bench seat in the rear which can be turned into a large air-sprung bed. A pop-up roof is also standard (electric assist is optional) providing standing height inside. An additional bed can be fitted in the pop-up roof area to increase sleeping capacity to four individuals. Fresh water and waste water tanks are accessible from outside the vehicle, while the gas-cylinder bay is hidden inside an interior cupboard. An auxiliary battery is included under the front passenger seat. Up to six optional individual seats can be fitted for maximum MPV flexibility, but only four seats (including the two-seater bench mentioned above) can be used when in camping mode.\n\nThe Marco Polo was designed and created in partnership with [[Westfalia]] just like Volkswagen camper vans were until 1999. It was then Daimler AG bought a controlling stake in the conversion company meaning Volkswagen had to continue converting their commercial vehicles into camper vans alone.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n====Viano X-Clusive (2008\u20132010)====\nThis edition was only available in European markets from 2008 to 2010 with either a petrol or diesel V6 engine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/xclusive.0004.html |title=Mercedes-Benz UK - Viano - Viano X-CLUSIVE |publisher=.mercedes-benz.co.uk |accessdate=4 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401211852/http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/xclusive.0004.html |archivedate=1 April 2010 }}</ref> It was available in either Brilliant Silver or Obsidian Black metallic paint, and featured a redesigned radiator grille, 18-inch alloy wheels, a chromed exhaust tailpipe, side skirts, and unique front and rear bumpers. The interior had pebble or anthracite coloured 'Twin' leather seats and a choice of grey or brown burr walnut wood accents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/xclusive.0003.html |title=Mercedes-Benz UK - Viano - Viano X-CLUSIVE |publisher=.mercedes-benz.co.uk |accessdate=4 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623060346/http://www2.mercedes-benz.co.uk/content/unitedkingdom/mpc/mpc_unitedkingdom_website/en/home_mpc/passengercars/home/new_cars/models/viano/639/xclusive.0003.html |archivedate=23 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n====Engines====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Years!! Model & Transmission !!Engine !!Power !!Torque !!Top Speed !!0-62&nbsp;mph (0-100 km/h) !!Economy !!Emissions\n|-\n!colspan=9|Diesel\n|-\n|2004\u20132007||'''Viano 2.0 CDI'''||2.2 L, 4 in-L||{{convert|109|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|290|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|99|mph|abbr=on}}||17.6 s||{{convert|31.7|mpgimp|l/100 km|abbr=on}}||235 g/km\n|-\n|2004\u20132007||'''Viano 2.0 CDI TouchShift'''||2.2 L, 4 in-L||{{convert|109|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|290|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|98|mph|abbr=on}}||17.3 s||{{convert|31.7|mpgimp|l/100 km|abbr=on}}||235 g/km\n|-\n|2007\u20132010||'''Viano 2.0 CDI'''||2.2 L, 4 in-L||{{convert|116|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}||{{convert|29