278<ref name=\"IMPD 2009 Annual Report\"/>\n| multinational   =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   = [[Joe Hogsett]]\n| minister1pfo    = [[List of mayors of Indianapolis, Indiana|Mayor of Indianapolis]]\n| minister2name   =\n| minister2pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Randal Taylor\n| chief1position  = Chief of Police\n| parentagency    = Indianapolis Department of Public Safety\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      = Division\n| officename      = {{Collapsible list |title=3 |Operations Division|Investigations Division|Administration/Professional Standards Division|}}\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     = District\n| stations        = {{Collapsible list |title=6 |Downtown District|Northwest District|North District|East District|Southwest District|Southeast District|}}\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    = Car\n| vehicles1       = 1,550| vehicle2type    = Motorcycle\n| vehicles2      = 70\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = [http://www.indy.gov/IMPD IMPD's official site]\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\n\nThe '''Indianapolis Metropolitan Police Department''' ('''IMPD''') is the law enforcement agency for the city of [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], in the United States. Its operational jurisdiction covers all of the consolidated city of Indianapolis and [[Marion County, Indiana|Marion County]] except for the [[Indianapolis International Airport|Airport Authority]] and the four excluded cities of [[Beech Grove, Indiana|Beech Grove]], [[Lawrence, Indiana|Lawrence]], [[Southport, Indiana|Southport]] and [[Speedway, Indiana|Speedway]] (see [[Unigov]]). The department was created on January 1, 2007, by consolidating the [[Indianapolis Police Department]] and the law enforcement division of the [[Marion County Sheriff's Office (Indiana)|Marion County Sheriff's Office]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indy.gov/agency/indianapolis-metropolitan-police-department|title=Indianapolis Metropolitan Police Department|website=City of Indianapolis|access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 IMPD made a lip sync video to [[Justin Timberlake]]'s \"[[Can't Stop the Feeling!]]\" in response to the Lip Sync Challenge.<ref>{{Citation|title=Can't Stop the Feeling - IMPD Lip Sync Challenge|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r_gX9MOETxg|language=en|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n[[File:Indianapolis Metropolitan police cruiser 2.jpg|thumb|250px|left|IMPD [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor|Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]]]]\nAt the time of its formation, the IMPD was headed by the elected sheriff of Marion County, [[Frank J. Anderson]]. However, on February 29, 2008, the department came under the control of the [[List of mayors of Indianapolis|mayor of Indianapolis]], [[Greg Ballard]],. after Ballard and Anderson reached a resolution for the transfer of power and the [[Indianapolis City-County Council|City-County Council]] passed Proposal 6 effecting the change. The IMPD is part of the Department of Public Safety. The mayor appoints the Director of Public Safety, who in turn appoints the Chief of Police to administer the daily operations of the department.\n\nIMPD has six service districts.\n\n===Downtown District===\nThe Downtown District is under the command of Commander Phillip Burton. Due to the nature of the area and the number of large events held here, this district relies heavily on foot, bicycle, and mounted patrol officers. The headquarters for the district is at 39 W. Jackson Street in the historic [[Indianapolis Union Station|Union Station]]. It is bounded by 10th Street and [[Interstate 65 in Indiana|I-65]] to the north, [[Interstate 70 in Indiana|I-70]]/I-65 to the east, Morris Street to the south, and the [[White River (Indiana)|White River]] to the west.\n\n* 80 sworn officers\n* 12,929 residents and an estimated 2,000,000 visitors in 2018\n*{{Convert|3.5|sqmi||abbr=}}\n* In 2018, Downtown District officers responded to 20,835 calls for service and proactively addressed an additional 20,014 incidents.\n\n===North District===\nThe North District is under the command of Commander Michael Wolley. It is bounded by 96th Street to the north; the city of [[Lawrence, Indiana|Lawrence]] to the east; Massachusetts Avenue, 30th Street, and [[Fall Creek (Indiana)|Fall Creek]] to the south; and [[Michigan Road]] to the west. Its headquarters is at 3120 E. 30th Street.\n\n* 198 sworn officers\n* 209,916 residents\n*{{Convert|79|sqmi||abbr=}}\n* In 2018, North District responded to 69,676 calls for service\n\n===East District===\nThe East District is under the command of Commander Richard Riddle. It is bounded by the city of Lawrence to the north; Carrol Road to the east; [[Washington Street (Indianapolis)|Washington Street]] and Brookville Road to the south; and I-65 and [[Meridian Street (Indianapolis)|Meridian Street]] to the west. The district maintains their headquarters at 201 N. Shadeland Avenue, also known as the Regional Operations Center or ROC.\n\n* 205 sworn officers\n* 145,489 residents\n*{{Convert|50|sqmi||abbr=}}\n* In 2018 East District responded to 81,121 calls for service.\n\n===Southeast District===\nThe Southeast District is under the command of Commander Ronald Hicks. It is bounded by Washington Street to the north; Carroll Road to the east; County Line Road to the South; and Meridian Street to the west. Headquarters for this district is located in [[Fountain Square, Indianapolis|Fountain Square]] at 1150 Shelby Street.\n\n* 160 sworn officers\n* 175,812 residents\n*{{Convert|85|sqmi||abbr=}}{{Convert|66|sqmi||abbr=}}\n* 60,217 calls for service were answered by Southeast District officers in 2018.\n\n===Southwest District===\nCommand for the Southwest District falls to Commander Susan Hill<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indy.gov/eGov/City/DPS/IMPD/Enforcement/Districts/Pages/Southwest.aspx|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> The district's northern boundary consists of 10th Street until the town of [[Speedway, Indiana|Speedway]], around Speedway until 16th Street, and following 16th to the White River; the eastern boundary is White River to Morris Street, then east until Meridian Street, and then south to County Line Road; the southern boundary is County Line Road; and the western boundary is Raceway Road. The district's headquarters is at 551 N. King Avenue.\n\n* 148 sworn officers\n* 136,680 residents\n*{{Convert|81|sqmi||abbr=}}\n* Southwest District answered 53,315 calls for service in 2018.\n\n===Northwest District===\nCommander Lorenzo Lewis <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indy.gov/eGov/City/DPS/IMPD/Enforcement/Districts/Pages/Northwest.aspx|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> is in command of the Northwest District. The boundaries for the district are 96th Street to the north; Michigan, I-65, and Meridian Street to the east; 10th Street, 16th Street, the Town of Speedway, and 10th Street again to the south; and Raceway Road to the west. The headquarters is at 3821 Industrial Boulevard.\n\n* 161 sworn officers\n* 143,395 residents\n*{{Convert|66|sqmi||abbr=}}\n* In 2018 Northwest District responded to 54,990 calls for service.\n\n===Special Units and Criminal Investigations===\nIn addition to the service districts detailed above, the department also maintains an Investigations Division for investigation of major crimes such as murder, rape, and those related to narcotics, gangs, or organized crime. The department also maintains five special units:\n\n* '''Aviation Section''' - Operates one helicopter to support vehicle patrols and pursuits.\n* '''Canine Section''' - Extensively trains dogs and handlers for use in police investigations and operations.\n* '''Mounted Patrol''' - Operates in downtown district primarily, serving areas not accessible to vehicle patrols.\n*'''Ranger Unit''' - Assigned to each district, these officers patrol the 200+ [[List of parks in Indianapolis|park properties in Indianapolis]].\n* '''[[SWAT]]''' - High-risk operations division divided into three sections: Snipers/Observers, Entry, and Tactical Emergency Medical Specialists (TEMS).\n\n==Rank structure==\n\nThe rank structure of the department is as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indy.gov/eGov/Council/Committees/Documents/IMPD%20STAFFING%20STUDY/January%2023/final%201-23-14%20staffing%20presentation-IMPD.pdf |title=Indianapolis Metropolitan Police Department Final 01-23-14 Staffing Presentation |last=Hite |first=Richard |access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Title\n!Insignia\n!Badge color\n!Uniform\n|-\n|[[Chief of Police]]\n|[[Image:2 Gold Stars.svg|center|54px]]\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Gold\n| rowspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Navy blue Shirt \n|-\n|Assistant Chief\n|[[Image:1 Gold Star.svg|center|27px]]\n|-\n|[[Deputy Chief]] \n|[[Image:Colonel Gold-vector.svg|center|50px]]\n|-\n|[[Commander]]\n|[[Image:US-O5 insignia.svg|center|27px]]\n|-\n|[[Major]] \n|[[Image:US-O4 insignia.svg|center|27px]]\n|-\n|[[Police captain|Captain]]\n|[[Image:Captain insignia gold.svg|center|25px]]\n|-\n|[[Lieutenant]]\n|[[Image:US-OF1B.svg|center|10px]]\n|-\n|[[Sergeant]]\n|[[File:NYPD Sergeant Stripes.svg|center|35px]]\n|-\n|[[Detective]]\n|\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Silver\n|-\n|[[Police Officer|Patrolman]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Weapons==\n*[[Glock 22]] [[.40 S&W]] was standard issue and was to be phased out in 2016, but following issues with the Glock 17M, the Glock 22 was put back into service until the issue could be addressed with Glock and the department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeone.com/police-products/firearms/articles/1638778-Indianapolis-officers-getting-new-Glocks-in-2008/|title=Indianapolis officers getting new Glocks in 2008|website=PoliceOne|access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Glock 17]]M [[9mm]] is the new issue weapon for 2016 and 2017. Currently all sworn officers have been issued the 17M and the Glock 22 has been completely phased out.\n*[[Remington 870]] Pump Action is the standard issue shotgun for the department. The department also uses a less lethal shotgun for certain situations where deadly force isn't needed but a [[Taser]] or pepper spray is ineffective.\n*[[AR-15]] is the patrol rifle utilized by the officers of the department during intense situations and other situations where a pistol or a shotgun is to little effect. The IMPD uses the Colt CAR-15A3 RO997 (M4A1) as does the agency's SWAT unit.\n\n== Fallen officers ==\n{{As of|2020|April|df=}}, there have been four Indianapolis Metropolitan police officers killed in the line of duty since the department was created in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/|title=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|website=Officer Down Memorial Page|access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indiana}}\n* [[List of law enforcement agencies in Indiana]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.indy.gov/IMPD Indianapolis Metropolitan Police Department site]\n* [http://www.indy.gov/eGov/City/DPS/IMPD/Enforcement/Districts/Pages/home.aspx IMPD Service Districts]\n* [http://www.indy.gov/eGov/City/DPS/IMPD/About/History/Documents/GeneralOrdinance110.pdf City-County General Ordinance No. 110, 2005]\n*[https://www.indy.gov/activity/police-department-annual-reports-statistics 2018 IMPD Annual Report] \n\n[[Category:Government of Indianapolis|Police]]\n[[Category:County police departments of Indiana]]\n[[Category:Municipal police departments of Indiana]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Paris1127", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indianapolis_Metropolitan_Police_Department"}
{"title_page": "Augustus Barry", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Augustus Barry\n|birth_date=1840\n|death_date=August 3, 1871\n|placeofburial=[[Cold Harbor National Cemetery]], [[Mechanicsville, Hanover County, Virginia]]\n|placeofburial_label=Place of burial\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place=[[Ireland]]\n|death_place= \n|allegiance={{flagicon|United States}} [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch=[[File:USArmy flag.jpg|25px]] [[United States Army]]<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|rank=[[File:Confederate States of America Sergeant Major-Infantry.jpg|25 px]] [[Sergeant Major]]\n|unit=[[16th U.S. Infantry|11th Regiment, U.S. Infantry]]\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]\n|awards=[[File:Medal of Honor ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Augustus Barry''' (1840 - August 3, 1871) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] soldier who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for valor during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nBarry served in the [[American Civil War]] in the [[16th U.S. Infantry]] for the [[Union Army]]. He received the Medal of Honor on February 28, 1870 for his actions in [[Tennessee]] and [[Georgia (U.S.state)|Georgia]] during the war.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n\n<blockquote>Gallantry in various actions during the rebellion.<ref>[http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/65/barry-augustus.php Congressional Medal of Honor Society]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|7902009}}\n*[http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=219 Military Times]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barry, Augustus}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1871 deaths]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States (before 1923)]]\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Augustus Barry\n|birth_date=1840\n|death_date=August 3, 1871\n|placeofburial=[[Cold Harbor National Cemetery]], [[Mechanicsville, Hanover County, Virginia]]\n|placeofburial_label=Place of burial\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place=[[Ireland]]\n|death_place= \n|allegiance={{flagicon|United States}} [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch=[[File:USArmy flag.jpg|25px]] [[United States Army]]<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|rank=[[File:Confederate States of America Sergeant Major-Infantry.jpg|25 px]] [[Sergeant Major]]\n|unit=[[16th U.S. Infantry]]\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]\n|awards=[[File:Medal of Honor ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Augustus Barry''' (1840 - August 3, 1871) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] soldier who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for valor during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nBarry served in the [[American Civil War]] in the [[16th U.S. Infantry]] for the [[Union Army]]. He received the Medal of Honor on February 28, 1870 for his actions in [[Tennessee]] and [[Georgia (U.S.state)|Georgia]] during the war.\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n\n<blockquote>Gallantry in various actions during the rebellion.<ref>[http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/65/barry-augustus.php Congressional Medal of Honor Society]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|7902009}}\n*[http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=219 Military Times]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barry, Augustus}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1871 deaths]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States (before 1923)]]\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustus_Barry"}
{"title_page": "A Shape of Light", "text_new": "{{cleanup|date=January 2019|reason=several redlinks}}\n{{short description|2018 album by Agraph}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Shape of Light\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Kensuke Ushio]]\n| cover      = A Silent Voice OST cover.jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = {{Start date|2016|9|14}}\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Maruna Studios]], [[Tokyo]]; [[Kimken Studios]]\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 119:20\n| label      = [[Pony Canyon]]\n| producer   = Pony Canyon, Kensuke Ushio\n| prev_title = [[Ping Pong (manga)|Ping Pong]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Liz and the Blue Bird]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | cover   = Alt cover A Shape of Light.jpg\n | border  = yes\n | alt     =\n | caption = The vinyl version [Shape A]\n}}\n}}\n'''A Shape of Light''' (full name '''A Shape of Light: A Silent Voice The Movie Original Soundtrack''') is the title of an album by Japanese [[Electronic body music|EBM]] musician and [[composer]] [[Kensuke Ushio]] which is the official movie soundtrack for Japanese animation movie ''[[A Silent Voice (film)|A Silent Voice]]''.\n\nThe Soundtrack contains 61 tracks on two [[Compact disc|CDs]] and has a running-time of about two hours. The album was released on September 14, 2016 via [[Pony Canyon]]. A western release was done in 2017 by [[Anime Limited]] in [[North America]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anime Limited Releasing Vinyl Soundtracks|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-10-27/anime-limited-releasing-vinyl-soundtracks/.123303|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Andrew Osmond|date=2017-10-27}}</ref>\n\n''A Shape of Light'' peaked at no. 74 on the [[Japanese Albums Chart]] where it lasted for about five weeks in the rankings.\n\n== Production history ==\nKensuke Ushio who creates [[Electronic body music|EBM]] music under his moniker ''agraph.'' was announced to be the soundtrack's composer in May 2016 after he got asked to write the music for [[Kyoto Animation]]'s anime movie ''[[A Silent Voice (film)|A Silent Voice]]'' back in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Silent Voice Anime Film Stars Miyu Irino, Saori Hayami|publisher=Anime News Network|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-05-27/a-silent-voice-anime-film-stars-miyu-irino-saori-hayami/.102548|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Chrystalyn Hodgkins|date=2016-05-27}}</ref><ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|title=Koe no Katachi: Interview with Kensuke Ushio.|publisher=Manga Tokyo|url=https://manga.tokyo/interview/koe-no-katachi-interview-with-kensuke-ushio/|accessdate=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\nMost of the tracks were composed by Ushio himself while all tracks called ''inv'' are based on the [[Inventions and Sinfonias (Bach)|Invention No. 1 in C mayor, BWV 772]] originally composed by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anime-Serien im Kino - Mein Abend mit der Suche nach Wiedergutmachung|publisher=[[Moviepilot.de]]|url=https://www.moviepilot.de/news/anime-serien-im-kino-mein-abend-mit-der-suche-nach-wiedergutmachung-196390|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Sven Raabe|date=2017-10-02}}</ref><ref name=\"VG\">{{cite web|title=\"a silent voice the movie\" original sound track: a shape of light [Shape B]|publisher=vgmdb.net|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/60312|accessdate=2019-01-12}}</ref> Ushio worked alongside movie director [[Naoko Yamada]] which had a very similar point of view when it came across the concept of the film and music.<ref name=\"InterviewUshio\">''Interview mit Kensuke Ushio (Musik)''. In: ''A Silent Voice \u2013 Deluxe Edition''. VIZ Media Switzerland SA (Kaz\u00e9 Anime), Berlin 2018, [[European Article Number|EAN]] 7630017513557.</ref> Kensuke Ushio described the movie as Sh\u014dyas story which deals about his contacts with other people and how treats them which was a universal theme when it cames to bring it out of context.<ref name=\"InterviewUshio\" /> For working on the films' music Ushio was shown several scenarios. He stated that he put full effort in the recordings of the sounds.<ref name=\"InterviewUshio\" />\n\nThe movie soundtrack was recorded at the [[Maruni Studios]] in [[Tokyo]]. The track ''slt'' featured guest musician [[Yuji Katsui]] on [[violin]]. The mixing of the first disc was done by [[Hiroshi Kitashiro]], while Ushio mixed the second CD himself. The mastering was done at [[Kimken Studios]].<ref name=\"VG\" />\n\nIn an interview Ushio stated he had not really worked on film scores that often before working on A Silent Voice's soundtrack.<ref name=\"MT\" /> Yamada who had known Ushio's music before contacted his management requesting his involvement in composing the soundtrack.<ref name=\"MT\" /> The work on the film's score began when most parts of the storyboard had to be elaborated.<ref name=\"MT\" /> The studio works ended when sound director [[Yuta Tsuruoka]] got the final musical concept and approved it.<ref name=\"MT\" />\n\n== Background ==\nUshio wrote 82 tracks in total for the soundtrack. 61 made it on the official soundtrack while 50 tracks are listenable during the movie. Most of the tracks are written for [[piano]].<ref name=\"MT\" />\n\nThe tracks' titles on the first CD contains of three letters, with exceptions of the ''inv'' titles, ''van(var)'', ''lvs(var)'' and ''lit(var)''. The three -letter titles are identification codes created by Ushio himself while composing the titles and which he got feedback for.<ref name=\"Ameba\">{{cite web|title=\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u66f2\u306f\u3001\u4eac\u30a2\u30cb\u8fd1\u304f\u306e\u6cb3\u539f\u3067\u6ce3\u304d\u306a\u304c\u3089\u601d\u3044\u3064\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u2015\u2015\u6620\u753b\u300e\u8072\u306e\u5f62\u300f\u97f3\u697d\u30fb\u725b\u5c3e\u61b2\u8f14\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|publisher=news.ameba.jp|url=https://news.ameba.jp/entry/20161008-597|accessdate=2019-01-12|date=2016-10-08|language=ja}}</ref> Ushio decided that he would use his identification codes as song names instead of renaming them in order to tell the listener their possible meanings. Instead he wanted the listeners to came up with their own interpretations.<ref name=\"Ameba\" />\n\nEven though those codes aren't arbitrary. So ''htb'' on the first CD stands for ''heart beat'' which is the first track on the second CD and another version of that track.<ref name=\"Ameba\" /> Ushio describes the ''inv'' tracks as the most important songs on the soundtrack.<ref name=\"KnK\">{{cite web|title=Music Interview|publisher=koenokatachi-movie.com|url=http://koenokatachi-movie.com/music/#music-interview|accessdate=2019-01-12|language=ja}}</ref> He stated that Bach's Invention is splitable in three parts as well as the movie's plot why every part got some ''inv'' tracks on it.<ref name=\"KnK\" />\n\nRegarding the movie the ''inv'' title and their adaptions is an example of learning how to communicate and how Sh\u014dya made it throughout the movie to overcome his guilt in Elementary School and how he invented a new way of communication.<ref name=\"KnK\" /> At the final scene on the movie where Sh\u014dya and Sh\u014dko are seen visiting the Highschool's culture festival the final part of Bach's ''Invention'' is played symbolising the end of Sh\u014dyas lession in communication.<ref name=\"KnK\" />\n\n''lit'' which is only played two times throughout the whole movie stands for ''Light''. Ushio stated the movie is about reaching the light which is why the songs was played at the very end of the film.<ref name=\"Ameba\" />\n\n== Tracklist ==\n{{Tracklist\n| headline         = CD 1\n| collapsed        = yes\n| total_length     = 60:48\n| Writer Spalte    = yes\n| title1           = tre\n| note1            = \n| writer1          = [[Kensuke Ushio]]\n| length1          = 01:48\n| title2           = inv(I.i)\n| note2            =\n| writer2          = [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n| length2          = 01:23\n| title3           = roh\n| note3        