= 01:41\n| title14          = green\n| note14           =\n| writer14         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length14         = 02:39\n| title15          = sunlight\n| note15           =\n| writer15         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length15         = 03:24\n| title16          = sketch no.19\n| note16           =\n| writer16         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length16         = 01:45\n| title17          = sustain\n| note17           =\n| writer17         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length17         = 02:08\n| title18          = no one here\n| note18           =\n| writer18         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length18         = 03:37\n| title19          = your silent portrait\n| note19           =\n| writer19         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length19         = 01:28\n| title20          = fractal\n| note20           =\n| writer20         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length20         = 05:45\n| title21          = flare\n| note21           =\n| writer21         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length21         = 02:18\n| title22          = speed of light\n| note22           = Music video on German DVD/BD version of [[A Silent Voice (film)|A Silent Voice]]\n| writer22         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length22         = 04:43\n}}\n\n== Critics ==\nThe soundtrack peaked at no. 74 in the [[Japanese Albums Chart]] at the week of September 14, 2016 where it was able to be for five weeks on the rankings.<ref>Charts: {{cite web|title=JP|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/432212/products/album/}}</ref>\n\nJames Marsh of [[South China Morning Post]] wrote that the discordant sounding score by Ushio lays an unsettling layer on the complex sounding landscape of the film which brings the viewer nearer to Sh\u014dko Nishimiyas world's view.<ref>{{cite web|title=Film review: A Silent Voice \u2013 Japanese animation takes sensitive look at perils of teenage life|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2084627/film-review-silent-voice-japanese-animation-take-sensitive-look|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=James Marsh|date=2017-04-17}}</ref> In a movie review at [[Anime News Network]] Kevin Cirugeda wrote that Kensuke Ushio and [[Naoko Yamada]] worked closely together on the soundtrack resulting \u2013 excluding the licensed ''[[My Generation]]'' by [[The Who]] \u2013 in gentle piano sounds, ambient sounds and pure silence. There are no significant tracks instead the films as whole was described as a sensory experience where the sounds play as such of a role like the background music used in the movie.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Silent Voice \u2013 Review|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/a-silent-voice/.108464|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Kevin Cirugeda|date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\nReaders of [[Anime UK News]] voted the soundtrack as ''Best Soundtrack'' at the [[Anime UK Reader\u2032s Choice Awards]] alongside the musical score of ''[[The Ancient Magus' Bride]]''.<ref name=\"AUKN\">{{cite web|title=Announcing the Anime UK News Readers\u2019 Choice Awards Winners!|publisher=Anime UK News|url=https://animeuknews.net/2018/01/readers-choice-awards-winners/|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Teapot, Demelza|date=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Animated film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:2016 albums]]\n[[Category:Electronic body music albums]]\n[[Category:Anime music]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|date=January 2019|reason=several redlinks}}\n{{short description|2018 album by Agraph}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Shape of Light\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Kensuke Ushio]]\n| cover      = A Silent Voice OST cover.jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = {{Start date|2016|9|14}}\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Maruna Studios]], [[Tokyo]]; [[Kimken Studios]]\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 119:20\n| label      = [[Pony Canyon]]\n| producer   = Pony Canyon, Kensuke Ushio\n| prev_title = [[Ping Pong (manga)|Ping Pong]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[Liz and the Blue Bird]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | cover   = Alt cover A Shape of Light.jpg\n | border  = yes\n | alt     =\n | caption = The vinyl version [Shape A]\n}}\n}}\n'''A Shape of Light''' (full name '''A Shape of Light: A Silent Voice The Movie Original Soundtrack''') is the title of an album by Japanese [[Electronic body music|EBM]] musician and [[composer]] [[Kensuke Ushio]] which is the official movie soundtrack for Japanese animation movie ''[[A Silent Voice (film)|A Silent Voice]]''.\n\nThe Soundtrack contains 61 tracks on two [[Compact disc|CDs]] and has a running-time of about two hours. The album was released on September 14, 2016 via [[Pony Canyon]]. A western release was done in 2017 by [[Anime Limited]] in [[North America]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anime Limited Releasing Vinyl Soundtracks|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-10-27/anime-limited-releasing-vinyl-soundtracks/.123303|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Andrew Osmond|date=2017-10-27}}</ref>\n\n''A Shape of Light'' peaked at no. 74 on the [[Japanese Albums Chart]] where it lasted for about five weeks in the rankings.\n\n== Production history ==\nKensuke Ushio who creates [[Electronic body music|EBM]] music under his moniker ''agraph.'' was announced to be the soundtrack's composer in May 2016 after he got asked to write the music for [[Kyoto Animation]]'s anime movie ''[[A Silent Voice (film)|A Silent Voice]]'' back in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Silent Voice Anime Film Stars Miyu Irino, Saori Hayami|publisher=Anime News Network|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-05-27/a-silent-voice-anime-film-stars-miyu-irino-saori-hayami/.102548|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Chrystalyn Hodgkins|date=2016-05-27}}</ref><ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|title=Koe no Katachi: Interview with Kensuke Ushio.|publisher=Manga Tokyo|url=https://manga.tokyo/interview/koe-no-katachi-interview-with-kensuke-ushio/|accessdate=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\nMost of the tracks were composed by Ushio himself while all tracks called ''inv'' are based on the [[Inventions and Sinfonias (Bach)|Invention No. 1 in C mayor, BWV 772]] originally composed by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anime-Serien im Kino - Mein Abend mit der Suche nach Wiedergutmachung|publisher=[[Moviepilot.de]]|url=https://www.moviepilot.de/news/anime-serien-im-kino-mein-abend-mit-der-suche-nach-wiedergutmachung-196390|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Sven Raabe|date=2017-10-02}}</ref><ref name=\"VG\">{{cite web|title=\"a silent voice the movie\" original sound track: a shape of light [Shape B]|publisher=vgmdb.net|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/60312|accessdate=2019-01-12}}</ref> Ushio worked alongside movie director [[Naoko Yamada]] which had a very similar point of view when it came across the concept of the film and music.<ref name=\"InterviewUshio\">''Interview mit Kensuke Ushio (Musik)''. In: ''A Silent Voice \u2013 Deluxe Edition''. VIZ Media Switzerland SA (Kaz\u00e9 Anime), Berlin 2018, [[European Article Number|EAN]] 7630017513557.</ref> Kensuke Ushio described the movie as Sh\u014dyas story which deals about his contacts with other people and how treats them which was a universal theme when it cames to bring it out of context.<ref name=\"InterviewUshio\" /> For working on the films' music Ushio was shown several scenarios. He stated that he put full effort in the recordings of the sounds.<ref name=\"InterviewUshio\" />\n\nThe movie soundtrack was recorded at the [[Maruni Studios]] in [[Tokyo]]. The track ''slt'' featured guest musician [[Yuji Katsui]] on [[violin]]. The mixing of the first disc was done by [[Hiroshi Kitashiro]], while Ushio mixed the second CD himself. The mastering was done at [[Kimken Studios]].<ref name=\"VG\" />\n\nIn an interview Ushio stated he had not really worked on film scores that often before working on A Silent Voice's soundtrack.<ref name=\"MT\" /> Yamada who had known Ushio's music before contacted his management requesting his involvement in composing the soundtrack.<ref name=\"MT\" /> The work on the film's score began when most parts of the storyboard had to be elaborated.<ref name=\"MT\" /> The studio works ended when sound director [[Yuta Tsuruoka]] got the final musical concept and approved it.<ref name=\"MT\" />\n\n== Background ==\nUshio wrote 82 tracks in total for the soundtrack. 61 made it on the official soundtrack while 50 tracks are listenable during the movie. Most of the tracks are written for [[piano]].<ref name=\"MT\" />\n\nThe tracks' titels on the first CD contains of three letters, with exceptions of the ''inv'' titles, ''van(var)'', ''lvs(var)'' and ''lit(var)''. The three -letter titles are identification codes created by Ushio himself while composing the titles and which he got feedback for.<ref name=\"Ameba\">{{cite web|title=\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u66f2\u306f\u3001\u4eac\u30a2\u30cb\u8fd1\u304f\u306e\u6cb3\u539f\u3067\u6ce3\u304d\u306a\u304c\u3089\u601d\u3044\u3064\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u2015\u2015\u6620\u753b\u300e\u8072\u306e\u5f62\u300f\u97f3\u697d\u30fb\u725b\u5c3e\u61b2\u8f14\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|publisher=news.ameba.jp|url=https://news.ameba.jp/entry/20161008-597|accessdate=2019-01-12|date=2016-10-08|language=ja}}</ref> Ushio decided that he would use his identification codes as song names instead of renaming them in order to tell the listener their possible meanings. Instead he wanted the listeners to came up with their own interpretations.<ref name=\"Ameba\" />\n\nEven though those codes aren't arbitrary. So ''htb'' on the first CD stands for ''heart beat'' which is the first track on the second CD and another version of that track.<ref name=\"Ameba\" /> Ushio describes the ''inv'' tracks as the most important songs on the soundtrack.<ref name=\"KnK\">{{cite web|title=Music Interview|publisher=koenokatachi-movie.com|url=http://koenokatachi-movie.com/music/#music-interview|accessdate=2019-01-12|language=ja}}</ref> He stated that Bach's Invention is splitable in three parts as well as the movie's plot why every part got some ''inv'' tracks on it.<ref name=\"KnK\" />\n\nRegarding the movie the ''inv'' title and their adaptions is an example of learning how to communicate and how Sh\u014dya made it throughout the movie to overcome his guilt in Elementary School and how he invented a new way of communication.<ref name=\"KnK\" /> At the final scene on the movie where Sh\u014dya and Sh\u014dko are seen visiting the Highschool's culture festival the final part of Bach's ''Invention'' is played symbolising the end of Sh\u014dyas lession in communication.<ref name=\"KnK\" />\n\n''lit'' which is only played two times throughout the whole movie stands for ''Light''. Ushio stated the movie is about reaching the light which is why the songs was played at the very end of the film.<ref name=\"Ameba\" />\n\n== Tracklist ==\n{{Tracklist\n| headline         = CD 1\n| collapsed        = yes\n| total_length     = 60:48\n| Writer Spalte    = yes\n| title1           = tre\n| note1            = \n| writer1          = [[Kensuke Ushio]]\n| length1          = 01:48\n| title2           = inv(I.i)\n| note2            =\n| writer2          = [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n| length2          = 01:23\n| title3           = roh\n| note3            =\n| writer3          = Kensuke Ushio\n| length3          = 01:46\n| title4           = lvs\n| note4            =\n| writer4          = Kensuke Ushio\n| length4          = 02:06\n| title5           = inv(I.ii)\n| note5            =\n| writer5          = J.S. Bach\n| length5          = 01:12\n| title6           = rev\n| note6            =\n| writer6          = Kensuke Ushio\n| length6          = 01:34\n| title7           = inv(I.iii)\n| note7            =\n| writer7          = J.S. Bach\n| length7          = 01:19\n| title8           = lvs(var)\n| note8            =\n| writer8          = Kensuke Ushio\n| length8          = 01:26\n| title9           = thn\n| note9            =\n| writer9          