         = 01:28\n| title20          = fractal\n| note20           =\n| writer20         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length20         = 05:45\n| title21          = flare\n| note21           =\n| writer21         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length21         = 02:18\n| title22          = speed of light\n| note22           = Music video on German DVD/BD version of [[A Silent Voice (film)|A Silent Voice]]\n| writer22         = Kensuke Ushio\n| length22         = 04:43\n}}\n\n== Critics ==\nThe soundtrack peaked at no. 74 in the [[Japanese Albums Chart]] at the week of September 14, 2016 where it was able to be for five weeks on the rankings.<ref>Charts: {{cite web|title=JP|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/432212/products/album/}}</ref>\n\nJames Marsh of [[South China Morning Post]] wrote that the discordant sounding score by Ushio lays an unsettling layer on the complex sounding landscape of the film which brings the viewer nearer to Sh\u014dko Nishimiyas world's view.<ref>{{cite web|title=Film review: A Silent Voice \u2013 Japanese animation takes sensitive look at perils of teenage life|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2084627/film-review-silent-voice-japanese-animation-take-sensitive-look|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=James Marsh|date=2017-04-17}}</ref> In an movie review at [[Anime News Network]] Kevin Cirugeda wrote that Kensuke Ushio and [[Naoko Yamada]] worked closely together on the soundtrack resulting \u2013 excluding the licensed ''[[My Generation]]'' by [[The Who]] \u2013 in gentle piano sounds, ambient sounds and pure silence. There are no significant tracks instead the films as whole was described as a sensory experience where the sounds play as such of a role like the background music used in the movie.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Silent Voice \u2013 Review|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/a-silent-voice/.108464|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Kevin Cirugeda|date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\nReaders of [[Anime UK News]] voted the soundtrack as ''Best Soundtrack'' at the [[Anime UK Reader\u2032s Choice Awards]] alongside the musical score of ''[[The Ancient Magus' Bride]]''.<ref name=\"AUKN\">{{cite web|title=Announcing the Anime UK News Readers\u2019 Choice Awards Winners!|publisher=Anime UK News|url=https://animeuknews.net/2018/01/readers-choice-awards-winners/|accessdate=2019-01-12|last=Teapot, Demelza|date=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Animated film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:2016 albums]]\n[[Category:Electronic body music albums]]\n[[Category:Anime music]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: an movie \u2192 a movie, titels \u2192 titles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Shape_of_Light"}
{"title_page": "Ella Castelhun", "text_new": "{{short description|American architect}}\n'''Ella Castelhun''' (1868\u20131961) was an American [[architect]] who operated primarily in [[San Francisco]] in the early 20th century.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1905, Castelhun became the second woman to be registered as an architect in the state of California. In addition to her career as an architect, Castelhun was also an artist, and is believed to have studied at the [[Mark Hopkins Institute of Art]] in San Francisco in the 1890s. In 1893, at the age of 25, Castelhun enrolled for the fall semester at the [[University of California]], Berkley. She graduated with a bachelor's degree in philosophy in 1898, and later became certified to teach high school. However, she continued her graduate studies in architecture and was licensed in 1905.<ref name=\"Horton\"/>\n\nOnly three buildings are specifically known to have been designed by Castelhun, three houses built for different women who were likely known to Castelhun.<ref name=\"Horton\">{{Cite book|title=Early Women Architects of the San Francisco Bay Area|last=Horton|first=Inge Schaefer|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|year=2010|isbn=978-0-7864-4656-8|location=North Carolina|pages=[https://archive.org/details/earlywomenarchit0000hort/page/189 189\u2013192]|url=https://archive.org/details/earlywomenarchit0000hort/page/189}}</ref> These include Olander House at 265-67 Lexington Street, San Francisco, built for Mathilda Olander; and 48-50 Merritt Street (now 3054-56 Market Street), built for Winifred McKeown.<ref name=\"Guidelines\">{{cite web|last1=Horton|first1=Inge S.|title=Ella Castelhun - A Lesser Known Woman Architect|url=http://www.sfcityguides.org/public_guidelines.html?article=593&submitted=TRUE&srch_text=&submitted2=&topic=B|website=Guidelines|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\nAnother house was built at 68 Palm Street, San Francisco, for Margaret Doyle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ella Castelhun: A Lesser-Known Woman Architect|url=https://www.womenarchitectsca.com/sample-biographies/ella-castelhun/|website=Women Architects in Northern California|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\nLikely due to difficulties in finding clients in the aftermath of World War 1, Castelhun gave up her architecture license in 1921.\n\nShe is buried in Mountain View Cemetery in Oakland.<ref name=\"Colbruno\">{{cite web|last1=Colbruno|first1=Michael|title=Ella Castelhun (1868-1961) \u2013 Second Woman Architect Licensed in California|url=http://mountainviewpeople.blogspot.com/2009/03/ella-castelhun-1868-1961-second-woman.html|website=Lives of the Dead: Mountain View Cemetery in Oakland|date=March 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castelhun, Ella}}\n[[Category:American architects]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Women architects]]\n[[Category:California women architects]]\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American architect}}\n'''Ella Castelhun''' (1868\u20131961) was an American [[architect]] who operated primarily in [[San Francisco]] in the early 20th century.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1905, Castelhun became the second woman to be registered as an architect in the state of California. In addition to her career as an architect, Castelhun was also an artist, and is believed to have studied at the [[Mark Hopkins Institute of Art]] in San Francisco in the 1890s. In 1893, at the age of 25, Castelhun enrolled for the fall semester at the [[University of California]], Berkley. She graduated with a bachelor's degree in philosophy in 1898, and later became certified to teach high school. However, she continued her graduate studies in architecture and was licensed in 1905.<ref name=\"Horton\"/>\n\nOnly three buildings are specifically known to have been designed by Castelhun, three houses built for different women who were likely known to Castelhun.<ref name=\"Horton\">{{Cite book|title=Early Women Architects of the San Francisco Bay Area|last=Horton|first=Inge Schaefer|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc.|year=2010|isbn=978-0-7864-4656-8|location=North Carolina|pages=[https://archive.org/details/earlywomenarchit0000hort/page/189 189\u2013192]|url=https://archive.org/details/earlywomenarchit0000hort/page/189}}</ref> These include Olander House at 265-67 Lexington Street, San Francisco, built for Mathilda Olander; and 48-50 Merritt Street (now 3054-56 Market Street), built for Winifred McKeown.<ref name=\"Guidelines\">{{cite web|last1=Horton|first1=Inge S.|title=Ella Castelhun - A Lesser Known Woman Architect|url=http://www.sfcityguides.org/public_guidelines.html?article=593&submitted=TRUE&srch_text=&submitted2=&topic=B|website=Guidelines|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\nAnother house was built at 68 Palm Street, San Francisco, for Margaret Doyle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ella Castelhun: A Lesser-Known Woman Architect|url=https://www.womenarchitectsca.com/sample-biographies/ella-castelhun/|website=Women Architects in Northern California|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\nLikely due to difficulties in finding clients in the aftermath of World War 1, Castelhun gave up her architecture license in 1921.\n\nShe is buried in Mountain View Cemetery in Oakland.<ref name=\"Colbruno\">{{cite web|last1=Colbruno|first1=Michael|title=Ella Castelhun (1868-1961) \u2013 Second Woman Architect Licensed in California|url=http://mountainviewpeople.blogspot.com/2009/03/ella-castelhun-1868-1961-second-woman.html|website=Lives of the Dead: Mountain View Cemetery in Oakland|date=March 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American architects]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Women architects]]\n[[Category:California women architects]]\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ella_Castelhun"}
{"title_page": "Oxymeris senegalensis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Oxymeris senegalensis 001.jpg\n| image_caption = Apertural view of a shell of ''Oxymeris senegalensis''\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia= clade [[Caenogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Hypsogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Neogastropoda]]\n| superfamilia = [[Conoidea]]\n| familia = [[Terebridae]]\n| subfamilia =\n| genus = ''[[Oxymeris]]''\n| species = '''''O. senegalensis'''''\n| binomial = ''Oxymeris senegalensis''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck|Lamarck]], 1822)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n*''Acus senegalensis'' <small>([[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck|Lamarck]], 1822)</small>\n* ''Duplicaria angolensis'' <small>(Aubry, 1999)</small>\n* ''Duplicaria sinae'' <small>Prelle, 2011</small>\n* ''Terebra angolensis'' <small>Aubry, 1999</small>\n*''Terebra cingula'' <small>[[Louis Charles Kiener|Kiener]], 1839</small>\n*''Terebra faval'' <small>Adanson, 1757</small>\n*''Terebra favat'' <small>d'Orbigny in Webb & Berthelot, 1839</small>\n*''Terebra festiva'' <small>[[G\u00e9rard Paul Deshayes|Deshayes]], 1857</small>\n*''Terebra fuscomaculata'' <small>Sowerby, 1825</small>\n*''Terebra senegalensis'' <small>[[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck|Lamarck]], 1822</small>\n*''Terebra speciosa'' <small>[[G\u00e9rard Paul Deshayes|Deshayes]], 1859</small>\n*''Terebra striatula'' <small>[[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck|Lamarck]], 1822</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Oxymeris senegalensis''''', common name : the '''Faval Auger''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Terebridae]], the auger snails.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|564246 |''Oxymeris senegalensis'' (Lamarck, 1822)||31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of an adult shell varies between 35&nbsp;mm and 165&nbsp;mm.\n{{Expand section|date=March 2011}}\n\n==Distribution==\nThis species occurs in the Atlantic Ocean from South [[Morocco]] to [[Angola]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Bouchet P. (1983 [\"1982\"]) ''Les Terebridae (Mollusca, Gastropoda) de l'Atlantique oriental.'' Bollettino Malacologico 18: 185\u2013216.\n* Bratcher T. & Cernohorsky W.O. (1987). ''Living terebras of the world. A monograph of the recent Terebridae of the world''. American Malacologists, Melbourne, Florida & Burlington, Massachusetts. 240pp\n* Gofas, S.; Afonso, J.P.; Brand\u00e0o, M. (Ed.). (S.a.). ''Conchas e Moluscos de Angola = Coquillages et Mollusques d'Angola. [Shells and molluscs of Angola]''. Universidade Agostinho / Elf Aquitaine Angola: Angola. 140 pp.\n* Terryn Y. (2007). ''Terebridae: A Collectors Guide''. Conchbooks & NaturalArt. 59pp + plates\n* Prelle G. (2011) Una nuova Duplicaria dal Camerun. Malacologia Mostra Mondiale 70: 17\u201318\n* Aubry U. (1999) Nuove terebre e antichi versi. Ancona: L'Informatore Piceno. 47 pp.\n* Terryn Y. & Ryall P. (2014) West African Terebridae, with the description of a new species from the Cape Verde Islands. Conchylia 44(3\u20134): 27\u201347\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/47433 Lamarck, J.-B. de. (1822). Histoire naturelle des animaux sans vert\u00e8bres, pr\u00e9sentant les caract\u00e8res g\u00e9n\u00e9raux et particuliers de ces animaux, leur distribution, leurs classes, leurs familles, leurs genres, et la citation des principales esp\u00e8ces qui s'y rapportent; pr\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9e d'une introduction offrant la d\u00e9termination des caract\u00e8res essentiels de l'animal, sa distinction du v\u00e9g\u00e9tal et des autres corps naturel; enfin, l'exposition des principes fondamentaux de la zoologie. Tome septi\u00e8me. 711 pp. Paris (Lamarck)]\n* [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/19855 Kiener L.C. (1834\u20131841). Sp\u00e9cies g\u00e9n\u00e9ral et iconographie des coquilles vivantes. Vol. 9. Famille des Purpurif\u00e8res. Deuxi\u00e8me partie. Genres Colombelle, (Columbella), Lamarck, pp. 1\u201363, pl. 1-16 &#91;pp. 1\u201363 (1841); pl. 2-4, 6, 8, 11 (1840), 1, 5, 7, 9\u201310, 12\u201316 (1841)&#93;; Buccin (Buccinum), Adanson, pp.&nbsp;1\u2013112 + table with duplicate page numbers 105\u2013108, pl. 1-31 &#91;pp.&nbsp;1\u201364 (1834), 65\u2013104 and 105\u2013108 of table (1835), 105\u2013112 of text (1841); pl. 1-24 (1834), 25\u201329 (1835), 30\u201331 (1841); Eburne (Eburna), Lamarck, pp.&nbsp;1\u20138, pl. 1-3 &#91;all (1835)&#93;; Struthiolaire (Struthiolaria), Lamarck, pp.&nbsp;1\u20136, pl. 1-2 &#91;pp&#93;. 1\u20136 (1838); pl. 1-2 (1837)&#93;; Vis (Terebra, Brugui\u00e8re, pp.&nbsp;1\u201342 + table, pl. 1-14 &#91;pp.&nbsp;1\u201342 (1838); pl. 1-14 (1837)&#93;. Paris, Rousseau & J.B. Bailli\u00e8re]\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=9|id=3989|title=''Acus senegalensis''|access-date=31 March 2011}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q6786069}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oxymeris Senegalensis}}\n[[Category:Terebridae]]\n[[Category:Molluscs of the Atlantic Ocean]]\n[[Category:Molluscs of Angola]]\n[[Category:Invertebrates of Guinea]]\n[[Category:Invertebrates of North Africa]]\n[[Category:Invertebrates of West Africa]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1822]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Jean-Baptiste Lamarck]]\n\n\n{{Terebridae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Oxymeris senegalensis 001.jpg\n| image_caption = Apertural view of a shell of ''Oxymeris senegalensis''\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia= clade [[Caenogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Hypsogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Neogastropoda]]\n| superfamilia = [[Conoidea]]\n| familia = [[Terebridae]]\n| subfamilia =\n| genus = ''[[Oxymeris]]''\n| species = '''''O. senegalensis'''''\n| binomial = ''Oxymeris senegalensis''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck|Lamarck]], 1822)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n*''Acus senegalensis'' <small>([[Jean-Baptiste La